THE WANDERER RETURNS:
Alfonso Duet had walked many roads since Thornheart Grove. Side quests, small adventures, the sort of meandering path that defined a wanderer's life. His steps eventually led him to Whiterun, where fate—or perhaps simply coincidence—intervened.
Danica recognized him immediately. The mage who had saved them at the Heart Tree. She brought him before the Jarl, insisting he was part of the adventuring company. Jarl Balgruuf, eager for progress, accepted her word. He provided Alfonso with his own writ and a brief summary: Lars Battleborn, kidnapped. The investigation team had last been seen leaving the city after speaking with the smiths at Warmaiden's.
Alfonso questioned Adrianne and Ulfberth, learned of the Gray-Mane hunting cabin, and set off alone.

THE REUNION AT THE CABIN:
Alfonso approached the isolated cabin cautiously, peering through the window. Inside, he could see his former companions—Davinia, Kyboah, Saijah—moving about the space. His face lit with genuine pleasure.
"Oh, hey!" he called out, pushing open the door. "How are you guys? Didn't expect to see you here!"
The party turned to face him, their expressions grim. Only then did Alfonso step fully inside and see the two corpses on the floor.
"Oh, nice," he said, his tone brightening. "We killing people?"
The silence that followed was heavy. Davinia gestured to the bodies, and the party began to explain. The investigation. The faked kidnapping. The ransom. The evidence pointing to Idolaf Battleborn—proud patriarch and war veteran—murdering both his own son and Hroggar Gray-Mane, then staging the scene to look like a murder-suicide.
Alfonso listened, nodded, and then crouched beside Hroggar's body with the detached curiosity of someone who had seen violence in all its forms.
"Look here," he said, pointing to the young man's arms. "Bruises. Defensive. Consistent with someone grabbing him, disarming him." He tilted his head, studying the angle of the crossbow bolt buried in Hroggar's chest. "And this shot... it's impossible. You can't self-inflict a bolt at this angle, not with a weapon like this. The mechanics don't work."
He moved to Lars's body next. "Single wound. Fatal. Blunt force trauma to the temple from striking the hearth." He ran a finger along the edge of the stone fireplace, then nodded to himself. "Accidental, most likely. A shove, a fall. Bad luck."
The party exchanged glances. Alfonso's observations confirmed what they had suspected but couldn't articulate. Idolaf had killed them both. But suspicion was not proof.
Alfonso rose and walked outside. The horse stood placidly near the cabin, its saddle ornate and well-maintained. He studied it for a long moment, then beckoned the others over.
"This saddle," he said. "Gray-Mane design. Distinctive. Anyone in Whiterun would recognize it immediately. This horse belonged to Hroggar's family."
Then the dog appeared, trotting up to them with its tail wagging uncertainly. Alfonso knelt and examined its muzzle. Red staining, faint but present, crusted in the fur around its mouth.
"Human blood," he said simply.
The pieces clicked into place. Lars's loyal dog had attacked Idolaf. The father had been wounded. That was the proof they needed.
The party made their decision quickly. Kyboah and Saijah would take their findings to the Jarl immediately. Davinia and Alfonso would remain at the cabin, protecting the crime scene from interference or tampering.

THE JARL'S FURY:
Kyboah and Saijah returned to Dragonsreach and laid out their case before Jarl Balgruuf. The faked kidnapping. The ransom paid. The staged scene at the cabin. The bruises on Hroggar's arms. The impossible angle of the bolt. The dog's bloody muzzle.
It was damning. It was compelling.
It was not definitive.
The Jarl's expression darkened with each word. When they finished, he did not thank them. He did not praise their diligence. Instead, he leaned forward, his knuckles white against the armrest of his throne.
"You come to me with theories," he said, his voice low and dangerous. "With suspicions. With circumstantial observations. But you bring me no proof. No irrefutable evidence. No confession." He rose to his feet, towering over them. "I gave you authority to investigate. I did not give you authority to accuse a Thane of murder based on blood on a dog's mouth and your interpretation of bruises."
His gaze swept over each of them. "You have until dawn. Bring me proof—real, undeniable proof—or you will be barred from this city, stripped of your pay, and your names will be spoken as failures who nearly tore Whiterun apart. Do you understand me?"
Kyboah and Saijah understood. They left Dragonsreach with the Jarl's ultimatum ringing in their ears.

THE VIGIL AND THE BANDITS:
Meanwhile, back at the cabin, Davinia and Alfonso maintained their watch. The sun dipped below the horizon, and the forest grew dark and quiet.
Then came the sound of footsteps. Careless. Loud.
Two bandits emerged from the trees, laughing between themselves, entirely unaware of the mages standing in the shadows. One of them drew a dagger and moved toward the horse, clearly intending to claim it as loot.
"Should've known," one muttered. "Abandoned cabin, free pickings—"
Alfonso's lightning struck first. A crackling arc of raw energy that lit the clearing like a miniature sun. The bandit convulsed, his scream cut short as his body seized and collapsed. Davinia's spell followed a heartbeat later, a second bolt that caught the other bandit mid-step. He dropped without a sound, smoke rising from his charred armor.
The entire encounter lasted three seconds.
Alfonso walked over to the corpses and knelt. He produced a knife.
"What are you doing?" Davinia asked, though her tone was more curious than alarmed.
"Waste not," Alfonso replied simply, and began carving.
Davinia watched for a moment, then turned away. Not from moral outrage—she had seen worse, done worse in the name of necessity—but from practicality. The smell of cooked flesh was unpleasant, and she had no desire for it to cling to her robes.
Alfonso ate methodically, efficiently, then wiped his blade clean and returned to his watch as if nothing unusual had occurred.

THE HUNT FOR PROOF:
Kyboah and Saijah made their way to the Battleborn estate, their purpose singular: examine Idolaf's wound. If they could prove it was a dog bite, they would have their evidence.
The Battleborn housecarl met them at the gate, his hand resting on his sword hilt. "The master is not receiving visitors."
Saijah produced the Jarl's Writ. The housecarl's expression soured, but he stepped aside. "He isn't here," he said grudgingly. "Left for Arcadia's Cauldron. Said he needed to restock his medical supplies."
Kyboah and Saijah exchanged a glance. Arcadia's Cauldron.
As they turned to leave, Davinia's voice echoed in Kyboah's mind—a strange, crystalline clarity that made him pause mid-step. Expert alteration magic, allowing thought to travel across distance.
"Bandits attacked the cabin. We handled it. Meet us at Arcadia's. We're all converging there."
Kyboah blinked, shook his head, and relayed the message to Saijah. Together, they ran for the marketplace.

ARCADIA'S REVELATION:
Arcadia's Cauldron was quiet when they arrived, the Imperial alchemist tending to her shelves with practiced efficiency. She looked up as the party filed in, her expression curious.
"Can I help you?"
"Idolaf Battleborn," Davinia said without preamble. "He came here recently. What did he buy?"
Arcadia hesitated, then sighed. "Canis Root Poultice. Paid double for it, too. Rush job." She crossed her arms. "It's a very specific remedy. Only really effective for one thing: infected animal bites."
The party stood in silence for a moment, the weight of the revelation settling over them.
They had him.
Saijah, with her Wood Elf affinity for animals, coaxed Lars's dog to follow them. The loyal hound came willingly, its tail wagging as if sensing it had a role yet to play.

THE WAR ROOM:
The great hall of Dragonsreach bustled with its usual traffic—courtiers whispering, petitioners waiting, guards at their posts. The party moved toward the throne, but before they could reach it, Irileth stepped into their path.
"You have news," the Dunmer housecarl stated. Her hand rested near her blade, her eyes reading their faces. "The Jarl is in a meeting. Come with me."
She turned without waiting for acknowledgment and led them up the grand staircase, past the Jarl's personal quarters, into the strategic heart of Dragonsreach. The war room was dominated by a massive table covered in maps of Skyrim, marked with troop positions and strategic points. The air smelled of ink and parchment and the weight of decisions that shaped kingdoms.
Jarl Balgruuf stood beside the table, and next to him stood a woman in Imperial legion armor—Legate Rikke, her bearing that of a soldier who had commanded armies. They both turned as the party entered, their conversation falling silent.
Balgruuf's eyes were hard. "Irileth said you have found something definitive. This had better be it. You are interrupting matters of great importance."
The party laid it out methodically. The faked kidnapping, proven by the mead bottles and the letter. The ransom note, hidden in Idolaf's study. The staged murder-suicide, made obvious by the impossible angle of the bolt and the bruises on Hroggar's arms. The horse with the Gray-Mane saddle. The dog with blood on its muzzle.
And finally, the purchase. Canis Root Poultice. Paid in haste. A remedy for one thing and one thing only.
Legate Rikke met the Jarl's gaze and gave a single, sharp nod. The case was undeniable.
Balgruuf's face set like stone. He turned to Irileth. "Bring Idolaf Battleborn before me. In the Great Hall. Now."

THE CONFRONTATION:
The scene shifted. The intimate strategy of the war room gave way to the public theater of the Great Hall. Jarl Balgruuf sat upon his throne, the party arrayed before him, when the guards brought Idolaf Battleborn through the great doors.
Idolaf Battleborn entered the hall with his head held high, but there was a brittleness to his composure. His left arm was bandaged, the wrappings fresh and clean.
"Jarl Balgruuf," he said, his voice steady. "I was told you summoned me. What is the meaning of this?"
The Jarl gestured to the party. "These investigators have made serious accusations. I would hear your response."
The party presented their evidence. Each piece, laid out like stones in a wall. Idolaf denied it all.
"The ransom note? A forgery. The cabin? I've never been there. The Canis Root Poultice? I cut myself sharpening a crossbow bolt in my grief. You've seen how careless sorrow makes a man."
Then Saijah stepped forward. She released the dog.
The hound bounded across the hall, tail wagging, and leapt at Idolaf with joyful recognition. Its teeth sank into his left arm—the exact spot where the bandage covered the wound. Idolaf screamed, staggering back, and Alfonso's hand flicked out. A whispered incantation, and the dog went limp, pacified by magic.
Idolaf clutched his bleeding arm, his face pale. "The animal is mad! It could have attacked anyone—"
"Then why," Kyboah said quietly, "did it go straight for the same wound you claim came from sharpening a bolt?"
The evidence was overwhelming. The purchase. The wound. The dog's reaction. Idolaf's denials grew weaker, more desperate.
Then Davinia delivered the final blow. "You hated them, didn't you? Your son and Hroggar. Their friendship. What it represented."
"No!" Idolaf's composure shattered like glass. "I loved my son! I would have done anything for him! Anything!"
"Then tell us what happened," Saijah said, her voice cold.
The words poured out of him in a broken torrent. "I just wanted to talk to him. To make him see reason. But he wouldn't listen, and I—I grabbed him, and he pulled away, and he fell. He hit his head. It was an accident. I swear to you, it was an accident."
"And Hroggar?" Kyboah asked.
"He came back. He saw Lars. He raised his crossbow. I had to protect myself. I disarmed him, and I—" Idolaf's voice broke. "I shot him. To protect my family's honor. To spare them the scandal. I staged it to look like they killed each other. I thought—I thought I could save us."
"By murdering a boy?" Davinia's voice was ice.
"I didn't mean to!" Idolaf screamed. "I loved him! I would never hurt my son!"
The guards moved forward and seized him. He struggled, still shouting, his voice echoing through the hall. "I loved him! I loved him!"

THE GRIM REWARD:
The great hall fell silent as Idolaf was dragged away. Jarl Balgruuf sat heavily upon his throne, his face carved from stone.
"You have done what I asked," he said, his voice weary. "You found the truth. The confession will prevent this from tearing my city apart." He gestured to his steward. "Pay them. And grant them access to the armory. They have earned it."
The gold was heavy in their hands. The enchanted items from the Jarl's personal collection were finely crafted and valuable. Yet the hall felt hollow, weighted with what had been uncovered.
The party left Dragonsreach in silence.

THE BANNERED MARE:
They sold the excess gear quickly, restocked their supplies, and made their way to the Bannered Mare. Falsetto was already there, her shimmering field of light drawing curious stares from the other patrons. Bjorn sat at a corner table, a steaming bowl of tomato and rice soup before him.
"There you are!" Falsetto said brightly. "I was beginning to think you'd gotten lost."
They sat, ordered food, and for a brief moment allowed themselves to simply exist without the weight of investigation pressing down on them.
Bjorn cleared his throat. "A courier found me earlier today," he said, producing two sealed letters. "One for me, one for you."
He opened his first. His eyes widened. "High King Torygg has summoned me to Solitude. Personal audience. He wants to discuss... trade contracts?" He looked bewildered. "I'm just a cart driver."
The party opened theirs. The seal was different—marked with the crest of Falkreath Hold.
"To the investigators who solved the Battleborn affair. The Jarl of Falkreath requests your immediate presence. A matter of great urgency requires skilled minds and capable hands. Payment and lodging will be provided. Make haste."
Kyboah set the letter down and picked up his soup. "Tomorrow," he said.
Tonight, they would drink, eat, and allow themselves the luxury of not thinking about fathers who killed their sons or the fragile peace of cities built on lies.
Tomorrow, they would ride for Falkreath.
But tonight, the soup was warm, the fire was bright, and the weight of justice—cold and merciless though it was—had been served.

